% You are an expert Python engineer. Your goal is to write the pdd/cli_detector.py module.

% Role & Scope
Detects and bootstraps agentic CLI harnesses (Claude CLI, Antigravity CLI (`agy`), Gemini CLI (legacy, retained for rollback), Codex CLI, OpenCode CLI) required for `pdd fix`, `pdd change`, `pdd bug`, and `pdd setup`. The primary entry point `detect_and_bootstrap_cli()` presents a numbered table of CLIs with install/key status, lets the user select one or more, and walks through installation and credential configuration for each. The legacy `detect_cli_tools()` function is preserved for backward compatibility. **Issue #1182 migration:** Antigravity is added as the supported successor to legacy Gemini CLI ahead of Google's 2026-06-18 consumer-tier Gemini CLI cutoff; the Gemini row is preserved during the rollback window so existing users are not broken by default.

% Requirements

1. Dataclass: `CliBootstrapResult` with fields `cli_name: str`, `provider: str`, `cli_path: str`, `api_key_configured: bool`, `skipped: bool` (default False). All strings default to empty.

2. Function: `detect_and_bootstrap_cli() -> List[CliBootstrapResult]` — Phase 1 entry point for `pdd setup`.
   a. Print a step banner via `_print_step_banner()` imported from `pdd.setup_tool`.
   b. Detect all five CLIs via `shutil.which()` with fallback to common paths (~/.local/bin, /usr/local/bin, /opt/homebrew/bin, ~/.antigravity/bin) and nvm node version directories.
   c. Provider mappings: anthropic->claude, antigravity->agy, google->gemini (legacy), openai->codex, opencode->opencode. Table order: Claude CLI, Antigravity CLI (`agy`), Gemini CLI (legacy), Codex CLI, OpenCode CLI.
   d. Print a numbered selection table showing install status and credential status per CLI, with aligned columns. Credential status reports: API key set (green ✓), or stored OAuth/subscription login configured (green ✓), or no credentials (red ✗).
   e. Accept comma-separated numeric input (e.g. "1,3"). Default to best available (installed+any-credential > installed > Claude). Any credential includes either API key OR stored OAuth login. "q"/"n" returns a skipped result.
   f. For each selected CLI, process install/credential/test in sequence. On skip or failure of one CLI, continue to the next.
   g. Install step: prompt user, run `npm install -g ...` via subprocess if accepted. Check npm availability first. Install commands are `npm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code`, `npm install -g @openai/codex`, `npm install -g @google/gemini-cli` (legacy Gemini), and `npm install -g opencode-ai`. **Antigravity has no npm install path:** for the `agy` row, do NOT attempt `npm install`; instead print a one-line install hint pointing the user at Google's native Antigravity installer (`https://antigravity.google/download` — the canonical install entry point), tell them to set `ANTIGRAVITY_API_KEY` or run the Antigravity sign-in flow to populate `~/.antigravity/oauth_creds.json`, then continue to the credential/test steps using whatever `agy` binary is currently on `$PATH`. Installing third-party binaries silently via subprocess would violate the explicit-consent contract for non-npm installers.
   h. Credential step: skip entirely when the CLI already has a stored OAuth/subscription credential (`_has_provider_oauth(provider)` returns True for the corresponding location: anthropic from `~/.claude/.credentials.json` or `~/Library/Application Support/Claude/credentials.json` or macOS keychain `Claude Code-credentials` or `CLAUDE_CODE_OAUTH_TOKEN` env; antigravity from `~/.antigravity/oauth_creds.json` (parse for a non-empty access/refresh token, swallowing `OSError`/`JSONDecodeError` and returning False, matching the gemini parse shape); google (legacy) from `~/.gemini/oauth_creds.json`; openai from `~/.codex/auth.json`; opencode from `~/.local/share/opencode/auth.json` only when it parses to non-empty provider credentials, or from global/project/env OpenCode config only when parsed JSON/JSONC declares a usable provider/model with resolvable auth or explicit local/no-key provider semantics). Issue #813 round-9 hardening: the anthropic file check MUST parse the credentials JSON shape via `_claude_credentials_file_has_oauth(path)` and require `claudeAiOauth.accessToken` or `claudeAiOauth.refreshToken` (or top-level fallback) to be non-empty — a bare size check (`stat().st_size > 0`) false-positives on stale, corrupt, or logged-out files that still contain bytes but no usable token, then `pdd setup` skips the API-key prompt and leaves the user with no working credential. The shape parse must swallow `OSError` and `JSONDecodeError` and return False. Match the parse style of the google/openai/opencode branches (they parse for known token/config keys rather than file size alone). Issue #813 root: prompting OAuth-only users for an API key here pushes them into the exact stale-key workflow this fix exists to make safe. When OAuth/config is detected without an API key, print a green confirmation that the stored credential/config will be used (for anthropic, also mention `PDD_KEEP_ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=1` as the opt-out for forcing API-key billing). Only when neither API key nor OAuth/config is present, prompt for an API key for normal providers, save to `~/.pdd/api-env.{shell}` with shell-appropriate syntax, add source line to RC file, set in `os.environ`. For OpenCode specifically, do NOT prompt for an `OPENCODE_API_KEY` because no such dedicated key exists; print a dim hint to run `opencode auth login`, configure a usable `~/.config/opencode/opencode.json` or project `opencode.json`, or set an underlying provider env var plus `OPENCODE_MODEL=provider/model`. Include the OpenCode docs URL `https://opencode.ai/docs/providers`.
   i. CLI test step (always runs, cannot be skipped): run `cli --version`, fall back to `--help` if that fails.
   j. Handle KeyboardInterrupt/EOFError at every input prompt gracefully.
   k. Return list of results; if empty, return `[CliBootstrapResult(skipped=True)]`.

3. Function: `detect_cli_tools() -> None` — legacy detection. For each CLI: show found/not-found status, cross-reference API keys, offer installation for missing CLIs that have matching keys.

4. Shell detection: detect from `SHELL` env var (default "bash"). Map to RC file: zsh->.zshrc, bash->.bashrc, fish->~/.config/fish/config.fish.

5. API key file management: create `~/.pdd/` if needed. Write keys to `~/.pdd/api-env.{shell}` (append, dedup by key name using regex). Add source line to RC file if not present. Shell syntax: bash/zsh use `export K=V`, fish uses `set -gx K V`. Source syntax: bash/zsh use `source path`, fish uses `test -f path ; and source path`.

6. Google provider (legacy Gemini row): primary env var is GEMINI_API_KEY (used by Gemini CLI for AI Studio auth). Fallback is GOOGLE_API_KEY (Vertex AI convention). Check GEMINI_API_KEY first, then GOOGLE_API_KEY. Primary key for saving is GEMINI_API_KEY. Display whichever is actually set.

6.1. Antigravity provider: `PROVIDER_PRIMARY_KEY["antigravity"]` is `ANTIGRAVITY_API_KEY` — a separate, dedicated primary key (do NOT alias to `GEMINI_API_KEY`/`GOOGLE_API_KEY` in setup until Antigravity non-interactive auth, settings/MCP layout, and model-selection semantics are verified). `_has_api_key("antigravity")` is True when `ANTIGRAVITY_API_KEY` is set with a non-empty value. `_has_provider_oauth("antigravity")` is True when `~/.antigravity/oauth_creds.json` parses to a non-empty access/refresh token (`OSError`/`JSONDecodeError` swallowed, returning False — same hardened shape as the Claude/Gemini parses). The install row points at Google's native Antigravity installer (no `npm install` command). On selection, the credential step offers (1) save `ANTIGRAVITY_API_KEY` to `~/.pdd/api-env.{shell}` or (2) skip and instruct the user to run the Antigravity sign-in flow to populate `~/.antigravity/oauth_creds.json`.

6.5. OpenCode provider: `PROVIDER_PRIMARY_KEY["opencode"]` is `None` because OpenCode reuses provider-specific credentials rather than an OpenCode-specific API key. `_has_api_key("opencode")` returns True only when at least one underlying provider credential environment variable is set. Build `_OPENCODE_PROVIDER_KEYS` from the non-empty `api_key` values in `pdd/data/llm_model.csv` (split pipe-delimited fields) and include known OpenCode-compatible extras such as `GITHUB_TOKEN`; do not hardcode only Anthropic/OpenAI/Gemini/OpenRouter. `_OPENCODE_PROVIDER_KEYS` represents environment-variable credentials only; it cannot and MUST NOT be used to represent catalog rows with no `api_key` value, local providers, or other no-key providers. Local/no-key support is handled by parsed OpenCode auth/config semantics in `_has_provider_oauth("opencode")`, not by `_OPENCODE_PROVIDER_KEYS`.

   `_has_provider_oauth("opencode")` parses `~/.local/share/opencode/auth.json` when present and returns True only when it contains non-empty provider credentials. It also parses OpenCode JSON/JSONC config sources (`~/.config/opencode/opencode.json`, nearest project `opencode.json`, `OPENCODE_CONFIG`, or `OPENCODE_CONFIG_CONTENT`) and returns True only when the parsed config declares a usable selected `model`/`provider` pairing backed by a resolvable credential (`options.apiKey`, `{env:...}` with a set env var, `{file:...}` with a readable non-empty file) or by explicit local/no-key provider semantics. Bare config file existence, valid config containing only preferences, and non-empty `OPENCODE_CONFIG_CONTENT` without a usable provider/model MUST NOT make credential status green. `OPENCODE_MODEL`, `OPENCODE_AGENT`, and `OPENCODE_VARIANT` are not credentials and must not make the key status green by themselves.

7. Module-level constants: `PROVIDER_PRIMARY_KEY`, `PROVIDER_DISPLAY`, `CLI_PREFERENCE`, `SHELL_RC_MAP` exposed for use by other modules. Extend `PROVIDER_PRIMARY_KEY`, `PROVIDER_DISPLAY`, and `CLI_PREFERENCE` to include `opencode` and `antigravity`; `PROVIDER_PRIMARY_KEY` must be typed as `Dict[str, Optional[str]]`. Display strings: `"OpenCode CLI"`, `"Antigravity CLI"`. `CLI_PREFERENCE` keeps Claude as the default first row, adds Antigravity, retains legacy Gemini below Antigravity for the rollback window, and includes OpenCode as a first-class selectable option. `PROVIDER_PRIMARY_KEY["antigravity"]` is `ANTIGRAVITY_API_KEY` (see Requirement 6.1).

% Dependencies

